3 — How the tokenomics / PoSim works (concept + flow)

3.1 Name suggestion

Proof-of-Simulation (PoSim) or Simwork or Proof-of-Valid-Simulation (PoVS). (Pick short: PoSim.)


3.2 High-level flow

1. Job creation: User (or marketplace) creates job spec S — includes world, robot, veil batch (portion of your 200 veils), params, random seed, expected metric baselines, and verifier policy. Job spec S is hashed: job_id = H(S).


2. Job broadcast: Job broadcast to network of worker nodes/miners.


3. Worker-run: Worker W runs the job, produces deterministic outputs over time (snapshots, checkpoints, final metrics). Worker records:

Checkpoint files C0, C1, ... Cn (deterministic, compressed).

Final metrics M and binary result (pass/fail safety checks).



4. Merkle root: Worker builds Merkle tree T over {metadata + checkpoints + metrics}. Worker signs root: R = MerkleRoot(T), produces signature = Sign_W(R).


5. Submission: Worker submits claim {job_id, worker_id, R, signature, proof_of_work?} to validators (or on-chain light record).


6. Verification: Validators fetch job spec S (from IPFS or registry), run lightweight verification (either recompute few checkpoints deterministically, validate Merkle path proofs, spot-check outputs, or re-run at lower fidelity). If threshold of validators attest → the claim is accepted.


7. Reward distribution: Smart contract mints tokens to the worker (and pays a cut to validators). Reputation/stake updated.


8. Auditability: Full records (Merkle root, validator attestations, baseline data) recorded on chain or decentralized storage. Anyone can re-run and verify later.



3.3 Key properties to avoid cheating

Determinism: Runs must be deterministic given job spec + seed. Use deterministic RNG seeds, fixed physics seeds and fixed simulator version.

Checkpoint hashing: Workers checkpoint every N steps; these checkpoints hashed into Merkle tree. Validators verify random subset of checkpoints to deter faking.

Stake & Slashing: Workers/validators stake tokens to participate. Proven misbehavior (invalid Merkle proofs, inconsistent outputs) results in slashing.

Replayability (light): Validators run a small deterministic subset or a lower-res replay to cheaply verify outputs.

Reputation: Reputation weights validator votes. New validators start with low trust, must build reputation.



